{"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib"]]},"primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"tokens":[{"text":"struct","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"RegexRef"}],"languages":["swift"],"platforms":["macOS"]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Overview","anchor":"overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"After instantiating a "},{"code":"GRegex","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", you can use its methods to find matches"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"in a string, replace matches within a string, or split the string at matches.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"GRegex","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" implements regular expression pattern matching using syntax and"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"semantics (such as character classes, quantifiers, and capture groups)"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"similar to Perl regular expression. See the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"man:pcre2pattern(3)","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" for details.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A typical scenario for regex pattern matching is to check if a string"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"matches a pattern. The following statements implement this scenario.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["const char *regex_pattern = \".*GLib.*\";","const char *string_to_search = \"You will love the GLib implementation of regex\";","`g_autoptr(GMatchInfo)` match_info = NULL;","`g_autoptr(GRegex)` regex = NULL;","","regex = g_regex_new (regex_pattern, G_REGEX_DEFAULT, G_REGEX_MATCH_DEFAULT, NULL);","g_assert (regex != NULL);","","if (g_regex_match (regex, string_to_search, G_REGEX_MATCH_DEFAULT, &match_info))","  {","    int start_pos, end_pos;","    g_match_info_fetch_pos (match_info, 0, &start_pos, &end_pos);","    g_print (\"Match successful! Overall pattern matches bytes `d` to `d`\\n\", start_pos, end_pos);","  }","else","  {","    g_print (\"No match!\\n\");","  }"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"{ .c }"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The constructor for ","type":"text"},{"code":"GRegex","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" includes two sets of bitmapped flags:"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"[flags"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/RegexCompileFlags","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":"]—These flags","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"control how GLib compiles the regex. There are options for case"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"sensitivity, multiline, ignoring whitespace, etc."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"[flags","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/RegexMatchFlags","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":"]—These flags control"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"GRegex","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"’s matching behavior, such as anchoring and customizing definitions","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for newline characters."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Some regex patterns include backslash assertions, such as ","type":"text"},{"code":"\\d","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" (digit) or"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"\\D","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" (non-digit). The regex pattern must escape those backslashes. For","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"example, the pattern ","type":"text"},{"code":"\"\\\\d\\\\D\"","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" matches a digit followed by a non-digit."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"GLib’s implementation of pattern matching includes a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"start_position"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"argument for some of the match, replace, and split methods. Specifying"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"a start position provides flexibility when you want to ignore the first","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"n","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" characters of a string, but want to incorporate backslash assertions"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"at character "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"n"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" - 1. For example, a database field contains inconsistent","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"spelling for a job title: "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"healthcare provider"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"health-care provider"},{"type":"text","text":"."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"The database manager wants to make the spelling consistent by adding a"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"hyphen when it is missing. The following regex pattern tests for the string","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"care"},{"type":"text","text":" preceded by a non-word boundary character (instead of a hyphen)"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and followed by a space.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"{ .c }","code":["const char *regex_pattern = \"\\\\Bcare\\\\s\";"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"An efficient way to match with this pattern is to start examining at","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"start_position","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" 6 in the string ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"healthcare"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"code":"health-care","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"{ .c }","code":["const char *regex_pattern = \"\\\\Bcare\\\\s\";","const char *string_to_search = \"healthcare provider\";","`g_autoptr(GMatchInfo)` match_info = NULL;","`g_autoptr(GRegex)` regex = NULL;","","regex = g_regex_new (","  regex_pattern,","  G_REGEX_DEFAULT,","  G_REGEX_MATCH_DEFAULT,","  NULL);","g_assert (regex != NULL);","","g_regex_match_full (","  regex,","  string_to_search,","  -1,","  6, \/\/ position of 'c' in the test string.","  G_REGEX_MATCH_DEFAULT,","  &match_info,","  NULL);"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The method [method","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.Regex.match_full"},{"type":"text","text":"] (and other methods implementing"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"start_pos"},{"text":") allow for lookback before the start position to determine if","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the previous character satisfies an assertion."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Unless you set the [flags"},{"code":"GLib.RegexCompileFlags.RAW","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"] as one of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GRegexCompileFlags"},{"type":"text","text":", all the strings passed to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GRegex"},{"type":"text","text":" methods must"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"be encoded in UTF-8. The lengths and the positions inside the strings are","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"in bytes and not in characters, so, for instance, "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\\xc3\\xa0"},{"text":" (i.e., ","type":"text"},{"code":"à","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":")","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"is two bytes long but it is treated as a single character. If you set","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"G_REGEX_RAW","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", the strings can be non-valid UTF-8 strings and a byte is","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"treated as a character, so "},{"code":"\\xc3\\xa0","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" is two bytes and two characters long.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Regarding line endings, ","type":"text"},{"code":"\\n","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" matches a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\\n"},{"type":"text","text":" character, and "},{"code":"\\r","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" matches","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\\r"},{"text":" character. More generally, ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\\R"},{"type":"text","text":" matches all typical line endings:"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"CR + LF ("},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\\r\\n"},{"type":"text","text":"), LF (linefeed, U+000A, "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\\n"},{"type":"text","text":"), VT (vertical tab, U+000B,"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"\\v","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"), FF (formfeed, U+000C, "},{"code":"\\f","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"), CR (carriage return, U+000D, "},{"code":"\\r","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"),"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"NEL (next line, U+0085), LS (line separator, U+2028), and PS (paragraph","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"separator, U+2029)."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The behaviour of the dot, circumflex, and dollar metacharacters are","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"affected by newline characters. By default, ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GRegex"},{"type":"text","text":" matches any newline"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"character matched by ","type":"text"},{"code":"\\R","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":". You can limit the matched newline characters by","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"specifying the [flags","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.RegexMatchFlags.NEWLINE_CR"},{"type":"text","text":"],"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"[flags","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.RegexMatchFlags.NEWLINE_LF"},{"text":"], and","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"[flags","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.RegexMatchFlags.NEWLINE_CRLF"},{"text":"] compile options, and","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"with [flags","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.RegexMatchFlags.NEWLINE_ANY"},{"text":"],","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"[flags","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.RegexMatchFlags.NEWLINE_CR"},{"text":"],","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"[flags","type":"text"},{"code":"GLib.RegexMatchFlags.NEWLINE_LF","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"] and","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"[flags","type":"text"},{"code":"GLib.RegexMatchFlags.NEWLINE_CRLF","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"] match options."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"These settings are also relevant when compiling a pattern if","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"[flags"},{"code":"GLib.RegexCompileFlags.EXTENDED","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"] is set and an unescaped","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"#","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" outside a character class is encountered. This indicates a comment"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"that lasts until after the next newline."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Because "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GRegex"},{"text":" does not modify its internal state between creation and","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"destruction, you can create and modify the same "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GRegex"},{"type":"text","text":" instance from"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"different threads. In contrast, [struct"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/MatchInfo","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"] is not thread safe."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The regular expression low-level functionalities are obtained through","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the excellent "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"http:\/\/www.pcre.org\/","type":"reference"},{"text":" library written by Philip Hazel.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/RegexRef","isActive":true},{"text":" type acts as a lightweight Swift reference to an underlying ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GRegex"},{"type":"text","text":" instance."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"It exposes methods that can operate on this data type through "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/RegexProtocol"},{"text":" conformance.","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Use "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/RegexRef","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" only as an ","type":"text"},{"code":"unowned","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" reference to an existing ","type":"text"},{"code":"GRegex","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" instance."}]},{"type":"aside","style":"note","name":"Note","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Use "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Regex","isActive":true},{"text":" (instead of ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/RegexRef"},{"text":") if you want to use Automatic Reference Counting for memory management of the underlying ","type":"text"},{"code":"GRegex","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" instance.","type":"text"}]}]}]}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/docum